
@startuml

' Define classes and their attributes

class Song {
    - title: String
    - year: int
    - length: float
    - genre: String
}

class Artist {
    - name: String (unique)
    - dateOfBirth: Date
    - url: String
}

class User {
    - id: String (unique)
    - name: String
    - address: String
}

class RegularUser {
}

class BusinessUser {
    - vatNumber: String
}

class Single {
}

class Hit {
}

class Album {
    - trackNumber: int
}

class Suggestion {
}

' Associations and relationships

Artist "1" -- "many" Song : creates
Song "1" -- "1" Artist : belongs to

User <|-- RegularUser
User <|-- BusinessUser

BusinessUser "1" -- "many" Song : uploads
Song "1" -- "1" BusinessUser : uploaded by

Song <|-- Single
Song <|-- Hit

Album "1" -- "many" Hit : contains
Hit "1" -- "1" Album : part of

RegularUser "1" -- "many" Single : buys
RegularUser "1" -- "many" Album : buys
RegularUser "1" -- "many" Suggestion : receives

Album "1" -- "many" Suggestion : suggested as

' Note: A user can be both a RegularUser and a BusinessUser, so no inheritance from both
' This is modeled with two separate subclasses from User.

@enduml

---

### ✅ Explanation of Key Design Decisions:
- **Artist-Song Relationship**: Each `Song` belongs to exactly one `Artist`, but multiple songs can have the same title. The unique key is the combination of `title` + `artist`.
- **User Types**: `User` is an abstract base class with two types: `RegularUser` and `BusinessUser`. Users can switch roles.
- **Song Subtypes**: Songs are split into `Single` and `Hit` to distinguish usage contexts.
- **Album Composition**: An `Album` is made only of `Hit` songs and stores their order via `trackNumber`.
- **Suggestion Logic**: Albums can be suggested to other users based on behavior.

